>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org", "@type": "WebPage",
    "name": "Apache Flink: Stream Processing, Windows & State Management",
    "url": "https://devplaybook.cc/tools/apache-flink",
    "description": "Complete Apache Flink guide covering DataStream API, event time, watermarks, windowing, stateful processing, Flink SQL, and comparison with Spark Streaming.",
  })} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Apache Flink: Stream Processing, Windows & State Management</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-6">
    <strong>Apache Flink</strong> is a true streaming engine that processes events one at a time with sub-millisecond latency, fault-tolerant managed state, and powerful windowing semantics. The framework of choice for fraud detection, real-time analytics, and event-driven architectures at scale.
  </p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> True event-by-event streaming</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Event time + watermarks</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Exactly-once semantics</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Managed state (RocksDB)</span>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">What is Apache Flink?</h2>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4 leading-relaxed">
    Apache Flink is an open-source, distributed stream processing framework developed at TU Berlin and now one of the most active Apache projects. Unlike Spark Structured Streaming which processes data in micro-batches, Flink processes each event individually as it arrives, achieving consistent sub-millisecond latency. Flink provides exactly-once processing guarantees through distributed snapshots (Chandy-Lamport algorithm), making it reliable for financial and mission-critical applications.
  </p>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4 leading-relaxed">
    Flink's key differentiator is managed state — stateful operations (running aggregates, session tracking, pattern matching) are stored in a configurable state backend and automatically checkpointed to durable storage. If a task fails, Flink restores state from the last checkpoint and replays from the source. Flink supports two primary APIs: the DataStream API for fine-grained control and Flink SQL for declarative streaming queries.
  </p>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">Window Types in Flink</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-muted space-y-1 mb-4 ml-2">
    <li><strong>Tumbling Window</strong> — fixed-size, non-overlapping windows (e.g., 1-minute buckets); every event belongs to exactly one window</li>
    <li><strong>Sliding Window</strong> — fixed-size, overlapping windows (e.g., 5-minute window every 1 minute); events can belong to multiple windows</li>
    <li><strong>Session Window</strong> — dynamic gap-based windows; a window closes when no event arrives within the gap timeout; ideal for user session analysis</li>
    <li><strong>Global Window</strong> — single unbounded window with a custom trigger; requires explicit trigger and evictor configuration</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mt-8 mb-3">DataStream API with Kafka Source</h2>
  <pre class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-4 text-xs font-mono overflow-x-auto whitespace-pre text-text mb-4" set:html={datastreamExample}></pre>

